# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: r-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This is an introduction to R (“GNU S”), a language and environment for statistical computing and graphics.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R is similar to the award-winning1 S system, which was developed at Bell Laboratories by John Chambers et al.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It provides a wide variety of statistical and graphical techniques (linear and nonlinear modelling, statistical tests, time series analysis, classification, clustering, ...).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This manual provides information on data types, programming elements, statistical modelling and graphics.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This introduction to R is derived from an original set of notes describing the S and S-PLUS environments written in 1990–2 by Bill Venables and David M.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Smith when at the University of Adelaide.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] We have made a number of small changes to reflect differences between the R and S programs, and expanded some of the material.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] We would like to extend warm thanks to Bill Venables (and David Smith) for granting permission to distribute this modified version of the notes in this way, and for being a supporter of R from way back.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Comments and corrections are always welcome.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Please address email correspondence to R-help@R-project.org.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Most R novices will start with A sample session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This should give some familiarity with the style of R sessions and more importantly some instant feedback on what actually happens.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Many users will come to R mainly for its graphical facilities.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] See Graphical procedures, which can be read at almost any time and need not wait until all the preceding sections have been digested.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R is an integrated suite of software facilities for data manipulation, calculation and graphical display.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The term “environment” is intended to characterize it as a fully planned and coherent system, rather than an incremental accretion of very specific and inflexible tools, as is frequently the case with other data analysis software.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R is very much a vehicle for newly developing methods of interactive data analysis.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It has developed rapidly, and has been extended by a large collection of *packages*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] However, most programs written in R are essentially ephemeral, written for a single piece of data analysis.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Our introduction to the R environment did not mention *statistics*, yet many people use R as a statistics system.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] We prefer to think of it of an environment within which many classical and modern statistical techniques have been implemented.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] A few of these are built into the base R environment, but many are supplied as *packages*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] There are about 25 packages supplied with R (called “standard” and “recommended” packages) and many more are available through the CRAN family of Internet sites (via https://CRAN.R-project.org) and elsewhere.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] More details on packages are given later (see Packages).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Most classical statistics and much of the latest methodology is available for use with R, but users may need to be prepared to do a little work to find it.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] There is an important difference in philosophy between S (and hence R) and the other main statistical systems.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In S a statistical analysis is normally done as a series of steps, with intermediate results being stored in objects.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Thus whereas SAS and SPSS will give copious output from a regression or discriminant analysis, R will give minimal output and store the results in a fit object for subsequent interrogation by further R functions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The most convenient way to use R is at a graphics workstation running a windowing system.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This guide is aimed at users who have this facility.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In particular we will occasionally refer to the use of R on an X window system although the vast bulk of what is said applies generally to any implementation of the R environment.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Most users will find it necessary to interact directly with the operating system on their computer from time to time.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In this guide, we mainly discuss interaction with the operating system on UNIX machines.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If you are running R under Windows or macOS you will need to make some small adjustments.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Setting up a workstation to take full advantage of the customizable features of R is a straightforward if somewhat tedious procedure, and will not be considered further here.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Users in difficulty should seek local expert help.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] When you use the R program it issues a prompt when it expects input commands.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The default prompt is ‘`>`’, which on UNIX might be the same as the shell prompt, and so it may appear that nothing is happening.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] However, as we shall see, it is easy to change to a different R prompt if you wish.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] We will assume that the UNIX shell prompt is ‘`$`’.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] At this point R commands may be issued (see later).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To quit the R program the command is > q() At this point you will be asked whether you want to save the data from your R session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] On some systems this will bring up a dialog box, and on others you will receive a text prompt to which you can respond yes, no or cancel (a single letter abbreviation will do) to save the data before quitting, quit without saving, or return to the R session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Data which is saved will be available in future R sessions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Use the R program, terminating with the `q()` command at the end of the session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To use R under Windows the procedure to follow is basically the same.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Create a folder as the working directory, and set that in the Start In field in your R shortcut.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Then launch R by double clicking on the icon.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Readers wishing to get a feel for R at a computer before proceeding are strongly advised to work through the introductory session given in A sample session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R has an inbuilt help facility similar to the `man` facility of UNIX.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For a feature specified by special characters, the argument must be enclosed in double or single quotes, making it a “character string”: This is also necessary for a few words with syntactic meaning including `if`, `for` and `function`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Either form of quote mark may be used to escape the other, as in the string `"It's important"`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Our convention is to use double quote marks for preference.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] which will launch a Web browser that allows the help pages to be browsed with hyperlinks.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] On UNIX, subsequent help requests are sent to the HTML-based help system.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The ‘Search Engine and Keywords’ link in the page loaded by `help.start()` is particularly useful as it is contains a high-level concept list which searches though available functions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It can be a great way to get your bearings quickly and to understand the breadth of what R has to offer.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The `help.search` command (alternatively `??`) allows searching for help in various ways.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Try `?help.search` for details and more examples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Technically R is an *expression language* with a very simple syntax.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It is *case sensitive* as are most UNIX based packages, so `A` and `a` are different symbols and would refer to different variables.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The set of symbols which can be used in R names depends on the operating system and country within which R is being run (technically on the *locale* in use).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Normally all alphanumeric symbols are allowed2 (and in some countries this includes accented letters) plus ‘`.`’ and ‘`_`’, with the restriction that a name must start with ‘`.`’ or a letter, and if it starts with ‘`.`’ the second character must not be a digit.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Names are effectively unlimited in length.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Elementary commands consist of either *expressions* or *assignments*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If an expression is given as a command, it is evaluated, printed (unless specifically made invisible), and the value is lost.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] An assignment also evaluates an expression and passes the value to a variable but the result is not automatically printed.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Commands are separated either by a semi-colon (‘`;`’), or by a newline.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Elementary commands can be grouped together into one compound expression by braces (‘`{`’ and ‘`}`’).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] *Comments* can be put almost3 anywhere, starting with a hash mark (‘`#`’), everything to the end of the line is a comment.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] on second and subsequent lines and continue to read input until the command is syntactically complete.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] We will generally omit the continuation prompt and indicate continuation by simple indenting.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Command lines entered at the console are limited4 to about 4095 bytes (not characters).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Under many versions of UNIX and on Windows, R provides a mechanism for recalling and re-executing previous commands.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The vertical arrow keys on the keyboard can be used to scroll forward and backward through a *command history*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Once a command is located in this way, the cursor can be moved within the command using the horizontal arrow keys, and characters can be removed with the DEL key or added with the other keys.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] More details are provided later: see The command-line editor.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The recall and editing capabilities under UNIX are highly customizable.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] You can find out how to do this by reading the manual entry for the **readline** library.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Alternatively, the Emacs text editor provides more general support mechanisms (via ESS, *Emacs Speaks Statistics*) for working interactively with R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] See R and Emacs in *R FAQ* for more information.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For Windows **Source** is also available on the **File** menu.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] will divert all subsequent output from the console to an external file, record.lis.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The entities that R creates and manipulates are known as *objects*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] These may be variables, arrays of numbers, character strings, functions, or more general structures built from such components.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] During an R session, objects are created and stored by name (we discuss this process in the next section).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] (alternatively, `ls()`) can be used to display the names of (most of) the objects which are currently stored within R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The collection of objects currently stored is called the *workspace*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] All objects created during an R session can be stored permanently in a file for use in future R sessions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] At the end of each R session you are given the opportunity to save all the currently available objects.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If you indicate that you want to do this, the objects are written to a file called .RData6 in the current directory, and the command lines used in the session are saved to a file called .Rhistory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] When R is started at later time from the same directory it reloads the workspace from this file.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] At the same time the associated commands history is reloaded.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It is recommended that you should use separate working directories for analyses conducted with R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It is quite common for objects with names `x` and `y` to be created during an analysis.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Names like this are often meaningful in the context of a single analysis, but it can be quite hard to decide what they might be when the several analyses have been conducted in the same directory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The simplest such structure is the numeric *vector*, which is a single entity consisting of an ordered collection of numbers.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] A number occurring by itself in an expression is taken as a vector of length one.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Notice that the assignment operator (‘`<-`’), which consists of the two characters ‘`<`’ (“less than”) and ‘`-`’ (“minus”) occurring strictly side-by-side and it ‘points’ to the object receiving the value of the expression.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In most contexts the ‘`=`’ operator can be used as an alternative.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Assignment can also be made using the function `assign()`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The usual operator, `<-`, can be thought of as a syntactic short-cut to this.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Assignments can also be made in the other direction, using the obvious change in the assignment operator.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If an expression is used as a complete command, the value is printed *and lost*8.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] the reciprocals of the five values would be printed at the terminal (and the value of `x`, of course, unchanged).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] would create a vector `y` with 11 entries consisting of two copies of `x` with a zero in the middle place.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Vectors can be used in arithmetic expressions, in which case the operations are performed element by element.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Vectors occurring in the same expression need not all be of the same length.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If they are not, the value of the expression is a vector with the same length as the longest vector which occurs in the expression.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] *Recycling* occurs in each binary operation: the shorter vector is recycled as often as need be (perhaps fractionally) until it matches the length of the longer vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In particular a constant is simply repeated.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] generates a new vector `v` of length 11 constructed by adding together, element by element, `2*x` repeated 2.2 times, `y` repeated just once, and `1` repeated 11 times.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The elementary arithmetic operators are the usual `+`, `-`, `*`, `/` and `^` for raising to a power.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In addition all of the common arithmetic functions are available.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] `log`, `exp`, `sin`, `cos`, `tan`, `sqrt`, and so on, all have their usual meaning.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] `max` and `min` select the largest and smallest elements of a vector respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] `range` is a function whose value is a vector of length two, namely `c(min(x), max(x))`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] `length(x)` is the number of elements in `x`, `sum(x)` gives the total of the elements in `x`, and `prod(x)` their product.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If the argument to `var()` is an *n*-by-*p* matrix the value is a *p*-by-*p* sample covariance matrix got by regarding the rows as independent *p*-variate sample vectors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] `sort(x)` returns a vector of the same size as `x` with the elements arranged in increasing order; however there are other more flexible sorting facilities available (see `order()` or `sort.list()` which produce a permutation to do the sorting).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Note that `max` and `min` select the largest and smallest values in their arguments, even if they are given several vectors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The *parallel* maximum and minimum functions `pmax` and `pmin` return a vector (of length equal to their longest argument) that contains in each element the largest (smallest) element in that position in any of the input vectors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For most purposes the user will not be concerned if the “numbers” in a numeric vector are integers, reals or even complex.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Internally calculations are done as double precision real numbers, or double precision complex numbers if the input data are complex.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To work with complex numbers, supply an explicit complex part.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] will do the computations as complex numbers.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R has a number of facilities for generating commonly used sequences of numbers.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The colon operator has high priority within an expression, so, for example `2*1:15` is the vector `c(2, 4, …, 28, 30)`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The construction `30:1` may be used to generate a sequence backwards.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function `seq()` is a more general facility for generating sequences.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] It has five arguments, only some of which may be specified in any one call.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The first two arguments, if given, specify the beginning and end of the sequence, and if these are the only two arguments given the result is the same as the colon operator.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Arguments to `seq()`, and to many other R functions, can also be given in named form, in which case the order in which they appear is irrelevant.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The next two arguments to `seq()` may be named `by=*value*` and `length=*value*`, which specify a step size and a length for the sequence respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] If neither of these is given, the default `by=1` is assumed.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The fifth argument may be named `along=*vector*`, which is normally used as the only argument to create the sequence `1, 2, …, length(*vector*)`, or the empty sequence if the vector is empty (as it can be).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] A related function is `rep()` which can be used for replicating an object in various complicated ways.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] which will put five copies of `x` end-to-end in `s5`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] which repeats each element of `x` five times before moving on to the next.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] As well as numerical vectors, R allows manipulation of logical quantities.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The elements of a logical vector can have the values `TRUE`, `FALSE`, and `NA` (for “not available”, see below).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The first two are often abbreviated as `T` and `F`, respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Note however that `T` and `F` are just variables which are set to `TRUE` and `FALSE` by default, but are not reserved words and hence can be overwritten by the user.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Hence, you should always use `TRUE` and `FALSE`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Logical vectors are generated by *conditions*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] sets `temp` as a vector of the same length as `x` with values `FALSE` corresponding to elements of `x` where the condition is *not* met and `TRUE` where it is.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In addition if `c1` and `c2` are logical expressions, then `c1 & c2` is their intersection (*“and”*), `c1 | c2` is their union (*“or”*), and `!c1` is the negation of `c1`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Logical vectors may be used in ordinary arithmetic, in which case they are *coerced* into numeric vectors, `FALSE` becoming `0` and `TRUE` becoming `1`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] However there are situations where logical vectors and their coerced numeric counterparts are not equivalent, for example see the next subsection.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In some cases the components of a vector may not be completely known.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] When an element or value is “not available” or a “missing value” in the statistical sense, a place within a vector may be reserved for it by assigning it the special value `NA`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In general any operation on an `NA` becomes an `NA`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The motivation for this rule is simply that if the specification of an operation is incomplete, the result cannot be known and hence is not available.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function `is.na(x)` gives a logical vector of the same size as `x` with value `TRUE` if and only if the corresponding element in `x` is `NA`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Notice that the logical expression `x == NA` is quite different from `is.na(x)` since `NA` is not really a value but a marker for a quantity that is not available.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Thus `x == NA` is a vector of the same length as `x` *all* of whose values are `NA` as the logical expression itself is incomplete and hence undecidable.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Note that there is a second kind of “missing” values which are produced by numerical computation, the so-called *Not a Number*, `NaN`, values.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] which both give `NaN` since the result cannot be defined sensibly.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In summary, `is.na(xx)` is `TRUE` *both* for `NA` and `NaN` values.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To differentiate these, `is.nan(xx)` is only `TRUE` for `NaN`s.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Missing values are sometimes printed as `<NA>` when character vectors are printed without quotes.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Character quantities and character vectors are used frequently in R, for example as plot labels.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Where needed they are denoted by a sequence of characters delimited by the double quote character, e.g., `"x-values"`, `"New iteration results"`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Character strings are entered using either matching double (`"`) or single (`'`) quotes, but are printed using double quotes (or sometimes without quotes).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] They use C-style escape sequences, using `\` as the escape character, so `\` is entered and printed as `\\`, and inside double quotes `"` is entered as `\"`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Other useful escape sequences are `\n`, newline, `\t`, tab and `\b`, backspace—see `?Quotes` for a full list.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Character vectors may be concatenated into a vector by the `c()` function; examples of their use will emerge frequently.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The `paste()` function takes an arbitrary number of arguments and concatenates them one by one into character strings.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Any numbers given among the arguments are coerced into character strings in the evident way, that is, in the same way they would be if they were printed.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The arguments are by default separated in the result by a single blank character, but this can be changed by the named argument, `sep=*string*`, which changes it to `*string*`, possibly empty.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Note particularly that recycling of short lists takes place here too; thus `c("X", "Y")` is repeated 5 times to match the sequence `1:10`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Subsets of the elements of a vector may be selected by appending to the name of the vector an *index vector* in square brackets.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] More generally any expression that evaluates to a vector may have subsets of its elements similarly selected by appending an index vector in square brackets immediately after the expression.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Such index vectors can be any of four distinct types.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] **A vector of positive integral quantities**.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] In this case the values in the index vector must lie in the set {1, 2, …, `length(x)`}.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The corresponding elements of the vector are selected and concatenated, *in that order*, in the result.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The index vector can be of any length and the result is of the same length as the index vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For example `x[6]` is the sixth component of `x` and > x[1:10] selects the first 10 elements of `x` (assuming `length(x)` is not less than 10).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Also > c("x","y")[rep(c(1,2,2,1), times=4)] (an admittedly unlikely thing to do) produces a character vector of length 16 consisting of `"x", "y", "y", "x"` repeated four times.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] **A vector of negative integral quantities**.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Such an index vector specifies the values to be *excluded* rather than included.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Thus > y <- x[-(1:5)] gives `y` all but the first five elements of `x`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This possibility only applies where an object has a `names` attribute to identify its components.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This option is particularly useful in connection with data frames, as we shall see later.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] An indexed expression can also appear on the receiving end of an assignment, in which case the assignment operation is performed *only on those elements of the vector*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The expression must be of the form `vector[*index_vector*]` as having an arbitrary expression in place of the vector name does not make much sense here.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Vectors are the most important type of object in R, but there are several others which we will meet more formally in later sections.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The entities R operates on are technically known as *objects*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Examples are vectors of numeric (real) or complex values, vectors of logical values and vectors of character strings.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] These are known as “atomic” structures since their components are all of the same type, or *mode*, namely *numeric*10, *complex*, *logical*, *character* and *raw*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Vectors must have their values *all of the same mode*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Thus any given vector must be unambiguously either *logical*, *numeric*, *complex*, *character* or *raw*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] (The only apparent exception to this rule is the special “value” listed as `NA` for quantities not available, but in fact there are several types of `NA`).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Note that a vector can be empty and still have a mode.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For example the empty character string vector is listed as `character(0)` and the empty numeric vector as `numeric(0)`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R also operates on objects called *lists*, which are of mode *list*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] These are ordered sequences of objects which individually can be of any mode.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] *lists* are known as “recursive” rather than atomic structures since their components can themselves be lists in their own right.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The other recursive structures are those of mode *function* and *expression*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Functions are the objects that form part of the R system along with similar user written functions, which we discuss in some detail later.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Expressions as objects form an advanced part of R which will not be discussed in this guide, except indirectly when we discuss *formulae* used with modeling in R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] By the *mode* of an object we mean the basic type of its fundamental constituents.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This is a special case of a “property” of an object.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Another property of every object is its *length*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The functions `mode(*object*)` and `length(*object*)` can be used to find out the mode and length of any defined structure 11.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Further properties of an object are usually provided by `attributes(*object*)`, see Getting and setting attributes.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Because of this, *mode* and *length* are also called “intrinsic attributes” of an object.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For example, if `z` is a complex vector of length 100, then in an expression `mode(z)` is the character string `"complex"` and `length(z)` is `100`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R caters for changes of mode almost anywhere it could be considered sensible to do so, (and a few where it might not be).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Now `d` and `z` are the same.12 There is a large collection of functions of the form `as.*something*()` for either coercion from one mode to another, or for investing an object with some other attribute it may not already possess.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The reader should consult the different help files to become familiar with them.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] An “empty” object may still have a mode.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] makes `e` an empty vector structure of mode numeric.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Similarly `character()` is a empty character vector, and so on.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Once an object of any size has been created, new components may be added to it simply by giving it an index value outside its previous range.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] now makes `e` a vector of length 3, (the first two components of which are at this point both `NA`).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This applies to any structure at all, provided the mode of the additional component(s) agrees with the mode of the object in the first place.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] This automatic adjustment of lengths of an object is used often, for example in the `scan()` function for input.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Conversely to truncate the size of an object requires only an assignment to do so.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] makes it an object of length 5 consisting of just the former components with even index.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] and vectors can be extended (by missing values) in the same way.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function `attributes(*object*)` returns a list of all the non-intrinsic attributes currently defined for that object.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function `attr(*object*, *name*)` can be used to select a specific attribute.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] These functions are rarely used, except in rather special circumstances when some new attribute is being created for some particular purpose, for example to associate a creation date or an operator with an R object.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The concept, however, is very important.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Some care should be exercised when assigning or deleting attributes since they are an integral part of the object system used in R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] When it is used on the left hand side of an assignment it can be used either to associate a new attribute with `*object*` or to change an existing one.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] allows R to treat `z` as if it were a 10-by-10 matrix.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] All objects in R have a *class*, reported by the function `class`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For simple vectors this is just the mode, for example `"numeric"`, `"logical"`, `"character"` or `"list"`, but `"matrix"`, `"array"`, `"factor"` and `"data.frame"` are other possible values.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] A special attribute known as the *class* of the object is used to allow for an object-oriented style13 of programming in R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For example if an object has class `"data.frame"`, it will be printed in a certain way, the `plot()` function will display it graphically in a certain way, and other so-called generic functions such as `summary()` will react to it as an argument in a way sensitive to its class.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To remove temporarily the effects of class, use the function `unclass()`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Only in rather special situations do you need to use this facility, but one is when you are learning to come to terms with the idea of class and generic functions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Generic functions and classes will be discussed further in Classes, generic functions and object orientation, but only briefly.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] A *factor* is a vector object used to specify a discrete classification (grouping) of the components of other vectors of the same length.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] R provides both *ordered* and *unordered* factors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] While the “real” application of factors is with model formulae (see Contrasts), we here look at a specific example.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Notice that in the case of a character vector, “sorted” means sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To find out the levels of a factor the function `levels()` can be used.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function `tapply()` is used to apply a function, here `mean()`, to each group of components of the first argument, here `incomes`, defined by the levels of the second component, here `statef`15, as if they were separate vector structures.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The result is a structure of the same length as the levels attribute of the factor containing the results.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The reader should consult the help document for more details.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Suppose further we needed to calculate the standard errors of the state income means.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To do this we need to write an R function to calculate the standard error for any given vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] (Writing functions will be considered later in Writing your own functions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] As an exercise you may care to find the usual 95% confidence limits for the state mean incomes.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] To do this you could use `tapply()` once more with the `length()` function to find the sample sizes, and the `qt()` function to find the percentage points of the appropriate *t*-distributions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function `tapply()` can also be used to handle more complicated indexing of a vector by multiple categories.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For example, we might wish to split the tax accountants by both state and sex.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] However in this simple instance (just one factor) what happens can be thought of as follows.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The values in the vector are collected into groups corresponding to the distinct entries in the factor.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The function is then applied to each of these groups individually.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The value is a vector of function results, labelled by the `levels` attribute of the factor.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The combination of a vector and a labelling factor is an example of what is sometimes called a *ragged array*, since the subclass sizes are possibly irregular.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] When the subclass sizes are all the same the indexing may be done implicitly and much more efficiently, as we see in the next section.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The levels of factors are stored in alphabetical order, or in the order they were specified to `factor` if they were specified explicitly.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] Sometimes the levels will have a natural ordering that we want to record and want our statistical analysis to make use of.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] The `ordered()` function creates such ordered factors but is otherwise identical to `factor`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p01] For most purposes the only difference between ordered and unordered factors is that the former are printed showing the ordering of the levels, but the contrasts generated for them in fitting linear models are different.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] An array can be considered as a multiply subscripted collection of data entries, for example numeric.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] R allows simple facilities for creating and handling arrays, and in particular the special case of matrices.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A dimension vector is a vector of non-negative integers.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If its length is *k* then the array is *k*-dimensional, e.g. a matrix is a *2*-dimensional array.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The dimensions are indexed from one up to the values given in the dimension vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A vector can be used by R as an array only if it has a dimension vector as its *dim* attribute.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Suppose, for example, `z` is a vector of 1500 elements.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] gives it the *dim* attribute that allows it to be treated as a *3* by *5* by *100* array.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Other functions such as `matrix()` and `array()` are available for simpler and more natural looking assignments, as we shall see in The `array()` function.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The values in the data vector give the values in the array in the same order as they would occur in FORTRAN, that is “column major order,” with the first subscript moving fastest and the last subscript slowest.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Arrays can be one-dimensional: such arrays are usually treated in the same way as vectors (including when printing), but the exceptions can cause confusion.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Individual elements of an array may be referenced by giving the name of the array followed by the subscripts in square brackets, separated by commas.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] More generally, subsections of an array may be specified by giving a sequence of *index vectors* in place of subscripts; however *if any index position is given an empty index vector, then the full range of that subscript is taken*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] `a[,,]` stands for the entire array, which is the same as omitting the subscripts entirely and using `a` alone.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] For any array, say `Z`, the dimension vector may be referenced explicitly as `dim(Z)` (on either side of an assignment).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Also, if an array name is given with just *one subscript or index vector*, then the corresponding values of the data vector only are used; in this case the dimension vector is ignored.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This is not the case, however, if the single index is not a vector but itself an array, as we next discuss.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] As well as an index vector in any subscript position, a matrix may be used with a single *index matrix* in order either to assign a vector of quantities to an irregular collection of elements in the array, or to extract an irregular collection as a vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A matrix example makes the process clear.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In the case of a doubly indexed array, an index matrix may be given consisting of two columns and as many rows as desired.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The entries in the index matrix are the row and column indices for the doubly indexed array.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In this case we need a *3* by *2* subscript array, as in the following example.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Negative indices are not allowed in index matrices.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] `NA` and zero values are allowed: rows in the index matrix containing a zero are ignored, and rows containing an `NA` produce an `NA` in the result.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] As a less trivial example, suppose we wish to generate an (unreduced) design matrix for a block design defined by factors `blocks` (`b` levels) and `varieties` (`v` levels).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Further suppose there are `n` plots in the experiment.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Index matrices must be numerical: any other form of matrix (e.g. a logical or character matrix) supplied as a matrix is treated as an indexing vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] would use `h` to set up *3* by *4* by *2* array in `Z`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] However if `h` is shorter than 24, its values are recycled from the beginning again to make it up to size 24 (see Mixed vector and array arithmetic.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The recycling rule) but `dim(h) <- c(3,4,2)` would signal an error about mismatching length.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] At this point `dim(Z)` stands for the dimension vector `c(3,4,2)`, and `Z[1:24]` stands for the data vector as it was in `h`, and `Z[]` with an empty subscript or `Z` with no subscript stands for the entire array as an array.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Arrays may be used in arithmetic expressions and the result is an array formed by element-by-element operations on the data vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The `dim` attributes of operands generally need to be the same, and this becomes the dimension vector of the result.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] makes `D` a similar array with its data vector being the result of the given element-by-element operations.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] However the precise rule concerning mixed array and vector calculations has to be considered a little more carefully.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The precise rule affecting element by element mixed calculations with vectors and arrays is somewhat quirky and hard to find in the references.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] From experience we have found the following to be a reliable guide.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] An important operation on arrays is the *outer product*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If `a` and `b` are two numeric arrays, their outer product is an array whose dimension vector is obtained by concatenating their two dimension vectors (order is important), and whose data vector is got by forming all possible products of elements of the data vector of `a` with those of `b`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The multiplication function can be replaced by an arbitrary function of two variables.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In particular the outer product of two ordinary vectors is a doubly subscripted array (that is a matrix, of rank at most 1).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Notice that the outer product operator is of course non-commutative.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Defining your own R functions will be considered further in Writing your own functions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] As an artificial but cute example, consider the determinants of *2* by *2* matrices *[a, b; c, d]* where each entry is a non-negative integer in the range *0, 1, ..., 9*, that is a digit.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The problem is to find the determinants, *ad - bc*, of all possible matrices of this form and represent the frequency with which each value occurs as a *high density* plot.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This amounts to finding the probability distribution of the determinant if each digit is chosen independently and uniformly at random.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Notice that `plot()` here uses a histogram like plot method, because it “sees” that `fr` is of class `"table"`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The “obvious” way of doing this problem with `for` loops, to be discussed in Grouping, loops and conditional execution, is so inefficient as to be impractical.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] It is also perhaps surprising that about 1 in 20 such matrices is singular.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `aperm(a, perm)` may be used to permute an array, `a`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The argument `perm` must be a permutation of the integers *{1, ..., k}*, where *k* is the number of subscripts in `a`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The result of the function is an array of the same size as `a` but with old dimension given by `perm[j]` becoming the new `j`-th dimension.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The easiest way to think of this operation is as a generalization of transposition for matrices.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] For this special case a simpler function `t()` is available, so we could have used `B <- t(A)`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] As noted above, a matrix is just an array with two subscripts.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] However it is such an important special case it needs a separate discussion.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] R contains many operators and functions that are available only for matrices.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] For example `t(X)` is the matrix transpose function, as noted above.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The functions `nrow(A)` and `ncol(A)` give the number of rows and columns in the matrix `A` respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The operator `%*%` is used for matrix multiplication.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] An *n* by *1* or *1* by *n* matrix may of course be used as an *n*-vector if in the context such is appropriate.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Conversely, vectors which occur in matrix multiplication expressions are automatically promoted either to row or column vectors, whichever is multiplicatively coherent, if possible, (although this is not always unambiguously possible, as we see later).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `crossprod()` forms “cross products”, meaning that `crossprod(X, y)` is the same as `t(X) %*% y` but the operation is more efficient.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If the second argument to `crossprod()` is omitted it is taken to be the same as the first.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The meaning of `diag()` depends on its argument.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] `diag(v)`, where `v` is a vector, gives a diagonal matrix with elements of the vector as the diagonal entries.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] On the other hand `diag(M)`, where `M` is a matrix, gives the vector of main diagonal entries of `M`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This is the same convention as that used for `diag()` in MATLAB.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Also, somewhat confusingly, if `k` is a single numeric value then `diag(k)` is the `k` by `k` identity matrix!
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Solving linear equations is the inverse of matrix multiplication.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] only `A` and `b` are given, the vector `x` is the solution of that linear equation system.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] solves the system, returning `x` (up to some accuracy loss).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Numerically, it is both inefficient and potentially unstable to compute `x <- solve(A) %*% b` instead of `solve(A,b)`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The quadratic form `x %*% A^{-1} %*% x` which is used in multivariate computations, should be computed by something like17 `x %*% solve(A,x)`, rather than computing the inverse of `A`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `eigen(Sm)` calculates the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a symmetric matrix `Sm`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The result of this function is a list of two components named `values` and `vectors`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Then `ev$val` is the vector of eigenvalues of `Sm` and `ev$vec` is the matrix of corresponding eigenvectors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] `evals` now holds the vector of eigenvalues and the second component is discarded.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] is used by itself as a command the two components are printed, with their names.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `svd(M)` takes an arbitrary matrix argument, `M`, and calculates the singular value decomposition of `M`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This consists of a matrix of orthonormal columns `U` with the same column space as `M`, a second matrix of orthonormal columns `V` whose column space is the row space of `M` and a diagonal matrix of positive entries `D` such that `M = U %*% D %*% t(V)`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] `D` is actually returned as a vector of the diagonal elements.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The result of `svd(M)` is actually a list of three components named `d`, `u` and `v`, with evident meanings.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] calculates the absolute value of the determinant of `M`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] after which we could use `absdet()` as just another R function.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] As a further trivial but potentially useful example, you might like to consider writing a function, say `tr()`, to calculate the trace of a square matrix. [Hint: You will not need to use an explicit loop.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `lsfit()` returns a list giving results of a least squares fitting procedure.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] gives the results of a least squares fit where `y` is the vector of observations and `X` is the design matrix.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] See the help facility for more details, and also for the follow-up function `ls.diag()` for, among other things, regression diagnostics.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Note that a grand mean term is automatically included and need not be included explicitly as a column of `X`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Further note that you almost always will prefer using `lm(.)` (see Linear models) to `lsfit()` for regression modelling.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Another closely related function is `qr()` and its allies.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] These compute the orthogonal projection of `y` onto the range of `X` in `fit`, the projection onto the orthogonal complement in `res` and the coefficient vector for the projection in `b`, that is, `b` is essentially the result of the MATLAB ‘backslash’ operator.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] It is not assumed that `X` has full column rank.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Redundancies will be discovered and removed as they are found.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This alternative is the older, low-level way to perform least squares calculations.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Although still useful in some contexts, it would now generally be replaced by the statistical models features, as will be discussed in Statistical models in R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] As we have already seen informally, matrices can be built up from other vectors and matrices by the functions `cbind()` and `rbind()`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Roughly `cbind()` forms matrices by binding together matrices horizontally, or column-wise, and `rbind()` vertically, or row-wise.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] the arguments to `cbind()` must be either vectors of any length, or matrices with the same column size, that is the same number of rows.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The result is a matrix with the concatenated arguments *arg_1*, *arg_2*, … forming the columns.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If some of the arguments to `cbind()` are vectors they may be shorter than the column size of any matrices present, in which case they are cyclically extended to match the matrix column size (or the length of the longest vector if no matrices are given).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `rbind()` does the corresponding operation for rows.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In this case any vector argument, possibly cyclically extended, are of course taken as row vectors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Suppose `X1` and `X2` have the same number of rows.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The result of `rbind()` or `cbind()` always has matrix status.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Hence `cbind(x)` and `rbind(x)` are possibly the simplest ways explicitly to allow the vector `x` to be treated as a column or row matrix respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] It should be noted that whereas `cbind()` and `rbind()` are concatenation functions that respect `dim` attributes, the basic `c()` function does not, but rather clears numeric objects of all `dim` and `dimnames` attributes.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This is occasionally useful in its own right.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] There are slight differences between the two, but ultimately the choice between them is largely a matter of style (with the former being preferable).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Recall that a factor defines a partition into groups.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Similarly a pair of factors defines a two way cross classification, and so on.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The function `table()` allows frequency tables to be calculated from equal length factors.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If there are *k* factor arguments, the result is a *k*-way array of frequencies.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Suppose, for example, that `statef` is a factor giving the state code for each entry in a data vector.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] gives in `statefr` a table of frequencies of each state in the sample.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The frequencies are ordered and labelled by the `levels` attribute of the factor.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Extension to higher-way frequency tables is immediate.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] An R *list* is an object consisting of an ordered collection of objects known as its *components*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] There is no particular need for the components to be of the same mode or type, and, for example, a list could consist of a numeric vector, a logical value, a matrix, a complex vector, a character array, a function, and so on.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Components are always *numbered* and may always be referred to as such.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Thus if `Lst` is the name of a list with four components, these may be individually referred to as `Lst[[1]]`, `Lst[[2]]`, `Lst[[3]]` and `Lst[[4]]`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If, further, `Lst[[4]]` is a vector subscripted array then `Lst[[4]][1]` is its first entry.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If `Lst` is a list, then the function `length(Lst)` gives the number of (top level) components it has.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This is a very useful convention as it makes it easier to get the right component if you forget the number.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Additionally, one can also use the names of the list components in double square brackets, i.e., `Lst[["name"]]` is the same as `Lst$name`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] It is very important to distinguish `Lst[[1]]` from `Lst[1]`. ‘`[[*…*]]`’ is the operator used to select a single element, whereas ‘`[*…*]`’ is a general subscripting operator.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Thus the former is the *first object in the list* `Lst`, and if it is a named list the name is *not* included.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The latter is a *sublist of the list `Lst` consisting of the first entry only.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The names of components may be abbreviated down to the minimum number of letters needed to identify them uniquely.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Thus `Lst$coefficients` may be minimally specified as `Lst$coe` and `Lst$covariance` as `Lst$cov`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The vector of names is in fact simply an attribute of the list like any other and may be handled as such.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Other structures besides lists may, of course, similarly be given a *names* attribute also.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] New lists may be formed from existing objects by the function `list()`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] sets up a list `Lst` of *m* components using *object_1*, …, *object_m* for the components and giving them names as specified by the argument names, (which can be freely chosen).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If these names are omitted, the components are numbered only.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The components used to form the list are *copied* when forming the new list and the originals are not affected.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Lists, like any subscripted object, can be extended by specifying additional components.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] When the concatenation function `c()` is given list arguments, the result is an object of mode list also, whose components are those of the argument lists joined together in sequence.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Recall that with vector objects as arguments the concatenation function similarly joined together all arguments into a single vector structure.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In this case all other attributes, such as `dim` attributes, are discarded.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A *data frame* is a list with class `"data.frame"`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A data frame may for many purposes be regarded as a matrix with columns possibly of differing modes and attributes.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] It may be displayed in matrix form, and its rows and columns extracted using matrix indexing conventions.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The simplest way to construct a data frame from scratch is to use the `read.table()` function to read an entire data frame from an external file.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This is discussed further in Reading data from files.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The `$` notation, such as `accountants$home`, for list components is not always very convenient.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A useful facility would be somehow to make the components of a list or data frame temporarily visible as variables under their component name, without the need to quote the list name explicitly each time.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The `attach()` function takes a ‘database’ such as a list or data frame as its argument.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Thus suppose `lentils` is a data frame with three variables `lentils$u`, `lentils$v`, `lentils$w`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] places the data frame in the search path at position 2, and provided there are no variables `u`, `v` or `w` in position 1, `u`, `v` and `w` are available as variables from the data frame in their own right.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] does not replace the component `u` of the data frame, but rather masks it with another variable `u` in the workspace at position 1 on the search path.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] However the new value of component `u` is not visible until the data frame is detached and attached again.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] More precisely, this statement detaches from the search path the entity currently at position 2.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Thus in the present context the variables `u`, `v` and `w` would be no longer visible, except under the list notation as `lentils$u` and so on.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In this way it is quite simple to work with many problems in the same directory, all of which have variables named `x`, `y` and `z`, for example.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] `attach()` is a generic function that allows not only directories and data frames to be attached to the search path, but other classes of object as well.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Anything that has been attached can be detached by `detach`, by position number or, preferably, by name.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Large data objects will usually be read as values from external files rather than entered during an R session at the keyboard.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] R input facilities are simple and their requirements are fairly strict and even rather inflexible.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] There is a clear presumption by the designers of R that you will be able to modify your input files using other tools, such as file editors or Perl19 to fit in with the requirements of R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] If variables are to be held mainly in data frames, as we strongly suggest they should be, an entire data frame can be read directly with the `read.table()` function.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] There is also a more primitive input function, `scan()`, that can be called directly.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] For more details on importing data into R and also exporting data, see *R Data Import/Export*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] To read an entire data frame directly, the external file will normally have a special form.
