[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] One convenient use of R is to provide a comprehensive set of statistical tables.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Functions are provided to evaluate the cumulative distribution function P(X <= x), the probability density function and the quantile function (given *q*, the smallest *x* such that P(X <= x) > q), and to simulate from the distribution.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Prefix the name given here by ‘d’ for the density, ‘p’ for the CDF, ‘q’ for the quantile function and ‘r’ for simulation (*r*andom deviates).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The first argument is `x` for `d*xxx*`, `q` for `p*xxx*`, `p` for `q*xxx*` and `n` for `r*xxx*` (except for `rhyper`, `rsignrank` and `rwilcox`, for which it is `nn`).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In not quite all cases is the non-centrality parameter `ncp` currently available: see the on-line help for details.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The `p*xxx*` and `q*xxx*` functions all have logical arguments `lower.tail` and `log.p` and the `d*xxx*` ones have `log`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] or more accurate log-likelihoods (by `d*xxx*(..., log = TRUE)`), directly.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] In addition there are functions `ptukey` and `qtukey` for the distribution of the studentized range of samples from a normal distribution, and `dmultinom` and `rmultinom` for the multinomial distribution.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Further distributions are available in contributed packages, notably **SuppDists**.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] See the on-line help on `RNG` for how random-number generation is done in R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Given a (univariate) set of data we can examine its distribution in a large number of ways.
