[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A stem-and-leaf plot is like a histogram, and R has a function `hist` to plot histograms.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] More elegant density plots can be made by `density`, and we added a line produced by `density` in this example.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The bandwidth `bw` was chosen by trial-and-error as the default gives too much smoothing (it usually does for “interesting” densities).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] We can plot the empirical cumulative distribution function by using the function `ecdf`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This distribution is obviously far from any standard distribution.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] How about the right-hand mode, say eruptions of longer than 3 minutes?
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Let us fit a normal distribution and overlay the fitted CDF.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Quantile-quantile (Q-Q) plots can help us examine this more carefully.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] This shows a reasonable fit but a shorter right tail than one would expect from a normal distribution.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] which will usually (if it is a random sample) show longer tails than expected for a normal.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Finally, we might want a more formal test of agreement with normality (or not).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] So far we have compared a single sample to a normal distribution.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] A much more common operation is to compare aspects of two samples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Note that in R, all “classical” tests including the ones used below are in package **stats** which is normally loaded.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Boxplots provide a simple graphical comparison of the two samples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The plot indicates that the first group tends to give higher results than the second.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] which does indicate a significant difference, assuming normality.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] By default the R function does not assume equality of variances in the two samples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] We can use the F test to test for equality in the variances, provided that the two samples are from normal populations.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] which shows no evidence of a significant difference, and so we can use the classical *t*-test that assumes equality of the variances.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] All these tests assume normality of the two samples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] The two-sample Wilcoxon (or Mann-Whitney) test only assumes a common continuous distribution under the null hypothesis.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] Note the warning: there are several ties in each sample, which suggests strongly that these data are from a discrete distribution (probably due to rounding).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] There are several ways to compare graphically the two samples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p02] We have already seen a pair of boxplots.
