[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] You will be asked if you want to save the R workspace, and for an exploratory session like this, you probably do not want to save it.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Users of R on Windows or macOS should read the OS-specific section first, but command-line use is also supported.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] or, via the `R CMD` interface, as a wrapper to various R tools (e.g., for processing files in R documentation format or manipulating add-on packages) which are not intended to be called “directly”.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] At the Windows command-line, `Rterm.exe` is preferred to `R`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] You need to ensure that either the environment variable `TMPDIR` is unset or it points to a valid place to create temporary files and directories.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Most options control what happens at the beginning and at the end of an R session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The startup mechanism is as follows (see also the on-line help for topic ‘Startup’ for more information, and the section below for some Windows-specific details).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] In addition, there are options for controlling the memory available to the R process (see the on-line help for topic ‘Memory’ for more information).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Users will not normally need to use these unless they are trying to limit the amount of memory used by R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] R accepts the following command-line options.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Print short help message to standard output and exit successfully.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Print version information to standard output and exit successfully.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Specify the encoding to be assumed for input from the console or `stdin`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This needs to be an encoding known to `iconv`: see its help page.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (`--encoding *enc*` is also accepted.) The input is re-encoded to the locale R is running in and needs to be representable in the latter’s encoding (so e.g. you cannot re-encode Greek text in a French locale unless that locale uses the UTF-8 encoding).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Print the path to the R “home directory” to standard output and exit successfully.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Apart from the front-end shell script and the man page, R installation puts everything (executables, packages, etc.) into this directory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Control whether data sets should be saved or not at the end of the R session.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] If neither is given in an interactive session, the user is asked for the desired behavior when ending the session with q(); in non-interactive use one of these must be specified or implied by some other option (see below).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Do not read any user file to set environment variables.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Do not read the site-wide profile at startup.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Do not read the user’s profile at startup.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Control whether saved images (file .RData in the directory where R was started) should be restored at startup or not.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Control whether the history file (normally file .Rhistory in the directory where R was started, but can be set by the environment variable `R_HISTFILE`) should be restored at startup or not.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (Windows only) Prevent loading the Rconsole file at startup.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Combine --no-save, --no-environ, --no-site-file, --no-init-file and --no-restore.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Under Windows, this also includes --no-Rconsole.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (not `Rgui.exe`) Take input from *file*: ‘-’ means `stdin`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Implies --no-save unless --save has been set.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] On a Unix-alike, shell metacharacters should be avoided in *file* (but spaces are allowed).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (not `Rgui.exe`) Use *expression* as an input line.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] One or more -e options can be used, but not together with -f or --file.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (There is a limit of 10,000 bytes on the total length of expressions used in this way.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Turn off command-line editing via **readline**.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This is useful when running R from within Emacs using the ESS (“Emacs Speaks Statistics”) package.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] See The command-line editor, for more information.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Command-line editing is enabled for default interactive use (see --interactive).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This option also affects tilde-expansion: see the help for `path.expand`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] For expert use only: set the initial trigger sizes for garbage collection of vector heap (in bytes) and *cons cells* (number) respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Suffix ‘M’ specifies megabytes or millions of cells respectively.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The defaults are 6Mb and 350k respectively and can also be set by environment variables `R_NSIZE` and `R_VSIZE`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Specify the maximum size of the pointer protection stack as *N* locations.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This defaults to 10000, but can be increased to allow large and complicated calculations to be done.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Currently the maximum value accepted is 100000.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Do not print out the initial copyright and welcome messages.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Additionally set `options("quiet")` or equivalently, `getOption("quiet")`, to `TRUE` which other R functions may use to be more quiet than usually.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This option is intended to support programs which use R to compute results for them.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Assert that R really is being run interactively even if input has been redirected: use if input is from a FIFO or pipe and fed from an interactive program.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (The default is to deduce that R is being run interactively if and only if stdin is connected to a terminal or `pty`.) Using -e, -f or --file asserts non-interactive use even if --interactive is given.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Note that this does not turn on command-line editing.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (Windows only) Set `Rterm` up for use by `R-inferior-mode` in ESS, including asserting interactive use (without the command-line editor) and no buffering of stdout.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Print more information about progress, and in particular set R’s option `verbose` to `TRUE`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] R code uses this option to control the printing of diagnostic messages.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Run R through debugger *name*.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] For most debuggers (the exceptions are `valgrind` and recent versions of `gdb`), further command line options are disregarded, and should instead be given when starting the R executable from inside the debugger.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Use *type* as graphical user interface (note that this also includes interactive graphics).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Currently, possible values for *type* are ‘X11’ (the default) and, provided that ‘Tcl/Tk’ support is available, ‘Tk’.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Run the specified sub-architecture.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This flag does nothing except cause the rest of the command line to be skipped: this can be useful to retrieve values from it with `commandArgs(TRUE)`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Note that input and output can be redirected in the usual way (using ‘<’ and ‘>’), but the line length limit of 4095 bytes still applies.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Warning and error messages are sent to the error channel (`stderr`).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The command `R CMD` allows the invocation of various tools which are useful in conjunction with R, but not intended to be called “directly”.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] where *command* is the name of the tool and *args* the arguments passed on to it.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Currently, the following tools are available.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Runs `R --restore --save` with possibly further options (see `?BATCH`).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Compile C, C++, Fortran … files for use with R.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Build shared library for dynamic loading.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Build (that is, package) add-on packages.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (UNIX only) Front-end for creating executable programs.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Convert Rd format to various other formats, including HTML, LaTeX, plain text, and extracting the examples.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] `Rd2txt` can be used as shorthand for `Rd2conv -t txt`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] to obtain usage information for each of the tools accessible via the `R CMD` interface.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] In addition, you can use options --arch=, --no-environ, --no-init-file, --no-site-file and --vanilla between `R` and `CMD`: these affect any R processes run by the tools.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (Here --vanilla is equivalent to --no-environ --no-site-file --no-init-file.) However, note that `R CMD` does not of itself use any R startup files (in particular, neither user nor site Renviron files), and all of the R processes run by these tools (except `BATCH`) use --no-restore.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Most use --vanilla and so invoke no R startup files: the current exceptions are `INSTALL`, `REMOVE`, `Sweave` and `SHLIB` (which uses --no-site-file --no-init-file).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] for any other executable `*cmd*` on the path or given by an absolute filepath: this is useful to have the same environment as R or the specific commands run under, for example to run `ldd` or `pdflatex`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Under Windows *cmd* can be an executable or a batch file, or if it has extension `.sh` or `.pl` the appropriate interpreter (if available) is called to run it.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] There are two ways to run R under Windows.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] `cmd.exe` or a more capable shell), the methods described in the previous section may be used, invoking by `R.exe` or more directly by `Rterm.exe`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] For interactive use, there is a console-based GUI (`Rgui.exe`).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The startup procedure under Windows is very similar to that under UNIX, but references to the ‘home directory’ need to be clarified, as this is not always defined on Windows.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] If the environment variable `R_USER` is defined, that gives the home directory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Next, if the environment variable `HOME` is defined, that gives the home directory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] After those two user-controllable settings, R tries to find system defined home directories.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] It first tries to use the Windows "personal" directory (typically `My Documents` in recent versions of Windows).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] If that fails, and environment variables `HOMEDRIVE` and `HOMEPATH` are defined (and they normally are) these define the home directory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Failing all those, the home directory is taken to be the starting directory.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] You need to ensure that either the environment variables `TMPDIR`, `TMP` and `TEMP` are either unset or one of them points to a valid place to create temporary files and directories.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Environment variables can be supplied as ‘*name*=*value*’ pairs on the command line.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] If there is an argument ending .RData (in any case) it is interpreted as the path to the workspace to be restored: it implies --restore and sets the working directory to the parent of the named file.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] (This mechanism is used for drag-and-drop and file association with `RGui.exe`, but also works for `Rterm.exe`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The following additional command-line options are available when invoking `RGui.exe`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Control whether `Rgui` will operate as an MDI program (with multiple child windows within one main window) or an SDI application (with multiple top-level windows for the console, graphics and pager).
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The command-line setting overrides the setting in the user’s Rconsole file.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Enable the “Break to debugger” menu item in `Rgui`, and trigger a break to the debugger during command line processing.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Under Windows with `R CMD` you may also specify your own .bat, .exe, .sh or .pl file.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] It will be run under the appropriate interpreter (Perl for .pl) with several environment variables set appropriately, including `R_HOME`, `R_OSTYPE`, `PATH`, `BSTINPUTS` and `TEXINPUTS`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] will run LaTeX on mydoc.tex, with the path to R’s share/texmf macros appended to `TEXINPUTS`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] There are two ways to run R under macOS.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] Within a `Terminal.app` window by invoking `R`, the methods described in the first subsection apply.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] There is also console-based GUI (`R.app`) that by default is installed in the `Applications` folder on your system.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] It is a standard double-clickable macOS application.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The startup procedure under macOS is very similar to that under UNIX, but `R.app` does not make use of command-line arguments.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] The ‘home directory’ is the one inside the R.framework, but the startup and current working directory are set as the user’s home directory unless a different startup directory is given in the Preferences window accessible from within the GUI.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] If you just want to run a file foo.R of R commands, the recommended way is to use `R CMD BATCH foo.R`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] If you want to run this in the background or as a batch job use OS-specific facilities to do so: for example in most shells on Unix-alike OSes `R CMD BATCH foo.R &` runs a background job.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] For further options see `help("Rscript")`.
[src:r-language/r-intro-p06] This writes R output to stdout and stderr, and this can be redirected in the usual way for the shell running the command.
